<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">26383605</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2016</Year><Month>08</Month><Day>22</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2022</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>31</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1466-447X</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>33</Volume><Issue>20</Issue><PubDate><Year>2015</Year></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Journal of sports sciences</Title><ISOAbbreviation>J Sports Sci</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Perceptions of well-being and physical performance in English elite youth footballers across a season.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>2106</StartPage><EndPage>2115</EndPage><MedlinePgn>2106-15</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1080/02640414.2015.1081393</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>The 2011 English Elite Player Performance Plan (EPPP) stipulates training volumes that could put elite youth players at high risk of non-functional overreaching. The aim of the study was to assess player perceptions of well-being and physical performance to these high training loads. Fourteen academy football players (mean &#xb1; SD: age 17 &#xb1; 1 years; stature 179 &#xb1; 6 cm; body mass 70.8 &#xb1; 8.6 kg, at pre-season) completed a perception of well-being questionnaire 1-4 times per week throughout each training block (pre-season, in-season 1, 2, 3). Physical performance tests were carried out at the end of each training block. Increases in training exposure (P &lt; 0.05; [Formula: see text] = 0.52) and moderate to large deteriorations in perceptions of well-being (motivation, sleep quality, recovery, appetite, fatigue, stress, muscle soreness P &lt; 0.05; [Formula: see text] = 0.30-0.53) were evident as the season progressed. A moderate decrease in 30 m sprint performance (P &lt; 0.05; [Formula: see text] = 0.48), a large improvement in Yo-Yo intermittent recovery test performance (P &lt; 0.05; [Formula: see text] = 0.93) and small decreases in countermovement jump (P &gt; 0.05; [Formula: see text] = 0.18) and arrowhead agility (P &lt; 0.05; [Formula: see text] = 0.24) performance were evident as the season progressed. The present findings show an imbalance between stress and recovery in English elite youth players even when players experience lower training exposure than stipulated by the EPPP.</AbstractText></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Noon</LastName><ForeName>Mark R</ForeName><Initials>MR</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Faculty of Health and Life Sciences , Coventry University , Coventry , UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>James</LastName><ForeName>Rob S</ForeName><Initials>RS</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Faculty of Health and Life Sciences , Coventry University , Coventry , UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Clarke</LastName><ForeName>Neil D</ForeName><Initials>ND</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Faculty of Health and Life Sciences , Coventry University , Coventry , UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Akubat</LastName><ForeName>Ibrahim</ForeName><Initials>I</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>b Department of Physical Education and Sports Studies , Newman University , Birmingham, UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Thake</LastName><ForeName>C Douglas</ForeName><Initials>CD</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>a Faculty of Health and Life Sciences , Coventry University , Coventry , UK.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author></AuthorList><Language>eng</Language><PublicationTypeList><PublicationType UI="D016428">Journal Article</PublicationType></PublicationTypeList><ArticleDate DateType="Electronic"><Year>2015</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>18</Day></ArticleDate></Article><MedlineJour